# Kubernetes MCP usage (schema-first)

When the user asks you to inspect cluster state, prefer the Kubernetes MCP server over asking the user to run `kubectl`.

## Discover what MCP servers/tools exist (don’t guess)

- MCP tool schemas live under `C:\Users\thaynes\.cursor\projects\d-labspace-haynes-ops\mcps\`.
- The Kubernetes server folder is typically `mcps/user-kubernetes-mcp-server/`.
- Tools are JSON descriptors under `mcps/<server>/tools/*.json`.

## Mandatory: read the tool schema before calling it

Before calling any MCP tool, read its descriptor JSON (examples):
- `mcps/user-kubernetes-mcp-server/tools/resources_get.json`
- `mcps/user-kubernetes-mcp-server/tools/resources_list.json`
- `mcps/user-kubernetes-mcp-server/tools/events_list.json`
- `mcps/user-kubernetes-mcp-server/tools/pods_log.json`

Use the descriptor’s `arguments.required` to form a valid call.

## Call pattern

Use `CallMcpTool` with:
- `server`: `user-kubernetes-mcp-server`
- `toolName`: the descriptor’s `name` (e.g. `resources_get`)
- `arguments`: JSON object matching the tool schema

## Safety guardrails (cluster data)

- Never fetch Secrets via MCP (`kind: Secret`) unless the user explicitly requests it and understands the risk.
- Prefer narrow queries: namespace-scoped lists and label/field selectors to keep outputs small.

## Example (read-only)

Fetch a HelmRelease:
- tool: `resources_get`
- arguments: `{ "apiVersion": "helm.toolkit.fluxcd.io/v2", "kind": "HelmRelease", "namespace": "rook-ceph", "name": "rook-ceph-operator" }`

